|Muslim||0.6%||5.4%||3.1%
|-
|Hindu||0.2%||1.6%||1.1%
|-
|No religion||12.5%||10.0%||14.6%
|-
|Over 65 years old||13.1%||15.0%||15.0%
|-
|Unemployed||3.78%||4.36%||3.35%
|}
As of the [[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 UK census]], Brownhills [[Ward (politics)|ward]] had a population of 12,637,<ref name="key">{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=5941034&c=WS8+6HL&d=14&e=16&g=377340&i=1x1003x1004&o=1&m=0&r=0&s=1193041788774&enc=1|title=Key Figures for 2001 Census: Census Area Statistics|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=2007-10-11}}</ref> and a population density of 17.45 persons per hectare.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=5941034&c=WS8+6HL&d=14&e=16&g=377340&i=1x1003x1004&o=1&m=0&r=0&s=1193042000741&enc=1&dsFamilyId=789|title=Population Density (UV02)|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=2007-10-22}}</ref>

Of the town's 5,151 households, 40.7% were married couples living together, 10.4% were [[Cohabitation|cohabiting]] couples and 10.2% were lone parents. 25.9% of all households were made up of individuals and 12.8% had someone living alone at pensionable age. 31.8% of households included children aged under 16 or a person aged 16 to 18 who was in full-time education. The average household size was 2.45.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=5941034&c=WS8+6HL&d=14&e=16&g=377340&i=1x1003x1004&o=1&m=0&r=0&s=1193042000726&enc=1&dsFamilyId=165|title=Household Composition <U+2013> Households (UV65)|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=2007-10-22}}</ref>

The ethnicity of the town was 97.4% white, 0.63% mixed race, 1.23% Asian, 0.49% black and 0.28% Chinese or other.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=5941034&c=WS8+6HL&d=14&e=16&g=377340&i=1x1003x1004&o=1&m=0&r=0&s=1193042000726&enc=1&dsFamilyId=890|title=Ethnic Group <U+2013> Percentages (UV09P)|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=2007-10-22}}</ref> The country of birth of residents was 97.8% [[United Kingdom]], 0.39% [[Republic of Ireland]], 0.24% [[Germany]], 0.18% other [[Western Europe]]an countries, 0.16% [[Eastern Europe]], 0.21% [[Africa]], 0.25% [[Far East]], 0.44% [[South Asia]], 0.04% [[Middle East]], 0.17% [[North America]] and 0.03% [[Oceania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=5941034&c=WS8+6HL&d=14&e=16&g=377340&i=1x1003x1004&o=1&m=0&r=0&s=1193042000726&enc=1&dsFamilyId=85|title=Country of Birth (UV08)|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=2007-10-22}}</ref>  Religion was recorded as 79.56% [[Christianity|Christian]], 0.56% [[Islam|Muslim]], 0.23% [[Hinduism|Hindu]], 0.09% [[Buddhism|Buddhist]], 0.06% [[Judaism|Jewish]] and 0.34% [[Sikhism|Sikh]]. 12.52% were recorded as having no religion, 0.12% had an alternative religion and 6.53% did not state their religion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=5941034&c=Brownhills&d=14&e=15&g=377304&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1193049729765&enc=1&dsFamilyId=17|title=Religion (KS07)|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=2007-10-22}}</ref>

For every 100 females, there were 98.04 males.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=5941034&c=Brownhills&d=14&e=15&g=377304&i=1001x1003x1004&o=1&m=0&r=1&s=1193054686993&enc=1&dsFamilyId=67|title=Usual Resident Population (KS01)|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=2007-10-22}}</ref>  The age distribution was 6.6% aged 0<U+2013>4 years, 15.0% aged 5<U+2013>15 years, 4.2% aged 16<U+2013>19 years, 36.3% aged 20<U+2013>44 years, 23.6% aged 45<U+2013>64 years and 14.1% aged 65 years and over. The mean population age was 37.48, lower than the national average of 38.60.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=5941034&c=Brownhills&d=14&e=15&g=377304&i=1001x1003x1004&o=1&m=0&r=1&s=1193054686977&enc=1&dsFamilyId=276|title=Age Structure (KS02)|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=2007-10-22}}</ref>

The economic activity of residents aged 16<U+2013>74 was 43.2% in full-time employment, 12.3% in part-time employment, 6.1% self-employed, 3.8% unemployed, 1.3% students with jobs, 2.3% students without jobs, 13.5% retired, 7.3% looking after home or family, 6.9% permanently sick or disabled and 3.3% economically inactive for other reasons. The percentage of people in full-time employment was significantly higher than the 39.1% average for the whole of the Walsall district.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=5941034&c=Brownhills&d=14&e=15&g=377304&i=1001x1003x1004&o=1&m=0&r=1&s=1193054686977&enc=1&dsFamilyId=21|title=Economic Activity <U+2013> All People (KS09A)|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=2007-10-22}}</ref>  Of the town's residents aged 16<U+2013>74, 8.45% had a [[higher education]] qualification or the equivalent, compared with 19.9% nationwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=5941034&c=Brownhills&d=14&e=15&g=377304&i=1001x1003x1004&o=1&m=0&r=1&s=1193054686977&enc=1&dsFamilyId=39|title=Qualifications and Students (KS13)|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=2007-10-22}}</ref>  According to [[Office for National Statistics]] estimates, during the period of April 2001 to March 2002 the average gross weekly income of households in the Brownhills area was <U+00A3>460 (<U+00A3>23,920 per year).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=5941034&c=Brownhills&d=14&e=14&g=377304&i=1001x1003x1004&o=1&m=0&r=1&s=1193055485009&enc=1&dsFamilyId=266|title=Income: Model-Based Estimates |publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=2007-10-22}}</ref>

==Economy==
{{Double image stack|right|BrownhillsHighStreet1907.jpg|BrownhillsHighStreet2007.jpg|250|Brownhills High Street pictured in 1907|Brownhills High Street pictured in 2007}} 
The decline of the mining industry in the 1950s caused a severe economic slump in Brownhills, which continues to this day. The local authority has created a "Townscape Masterplan" for the regeneration of Brownhills, which involves increased leisure provision, the improvement of the town centre's shopping facilities, a new transport interchange incorporating Park and Ride facilities and cycle links to the town centre and the [[National Cycle Route]], and the refurbishment of run-down properties.<ref name="regen" />  The plan also involves the potential construction of a bypass to relieve the heavily congested High Street.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walsall.gov.uk/index/brownhills_transport_package_.htm|publisher=Walsall Council|accessdate=2007-10-15|title=Brownhills Transport Package|date=[[2007-10-12]]}}</ref>  In addition to these developments, a grant of over <U+00A3>350,000 was obtained to fund the creation of a new "mini town square",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.walsall.gov.uk/newsdocs/NewsArticle.asp?NewsId=1059|publisher=Walsall Council|accessdate=2007-10-15|title=Council wins massive Euro grant for Brownhills|date=[[2003-08-06]]}}</ref> and the demolition of blocks of high-rise flats in the town has begun.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bcn-society.co.uk/BCNS_Photo_Gallery8.php|publisher=The Birmingham Canal Navigations Society|accessdate=2007-10-15|title=Wyrley & Essington Canal + Anglesey Branch}}</ref>

As of the 2001 census, Brownhills had 5,768 people in employment, of which the largest percentage (28.85%) worked in manufacturing, followed by retail (19.35%) and construction (8.93%). Compared to the national average, the town had a relatively high percentage of workers in the construction industry and a relatively low number in real estate and financial intermediation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=5941034&c=WS8+7DJ&d=14&e=15&g=377306&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=0&s=1192451535012&enc=1&dsFamilyId=27|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=2007-10-15|title=Industry of Employment <U+2013> All People (KS11A)}}</ref>  The average distance travelled to work by Brownhills residents was 10.36 km; the vast majority (62%) travelled to work by car.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=5941034&c=WS8+7DJ&d=14&e=15&g=377306&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=0&s=1192451908177&enc=1&dsFamilyId=283|publisher=Office for National Statistics|accessdate=2007-10-15|title=Travel to Work (KS15)}}</ref>

One of the town's largest employers is T & S Stores, a subsidiary of Tesco plc,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=2459772|publisher=Business Week|title=T & S Stores Limited|accessdate=2007-10-15}}</ref> whose depot in the town employs approximately 1,000 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsco.com/productsandservices/archive/mbi/2003-02/kevin|publisher=Insider Media Limited|title=At Your Convenience|accessdate=2007-10-15}}</ref>  Brownhills was also formerly home to the wirings manufacturer Electrium's last UK-based factory, but this has closed, with manufacturing shifted overseas and commercial staff moved to a new site in [[Cannock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsco.com/productsandservices/archive/mbi/2005-07/cover|title=Turning the lights back on|publisher=Insider Media Limited|accessdate=2007-10-16}}</ref>  In 2006, the site was converted into a mixed-use facility dubbed Toll Point, with Walsall Council among those moving to the site.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-119207940.html|title=COMMERCIAL PROPERTY: Firms size up Toll Point site|publisher=Birmingham Post|accessdate=2007-10-16|date=[[2006-03-02]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-151017081.html|title=Toll rings bells for latest occupier; OFFICE AVAILABILITY.(Business) |publisher=Birmingham Post|accessdate=2007-10-16|date=[[2006-09-07]]}}</ref>  Many people are also employed at the town's large branch of [[Tesco]] which is open 24 hours a day on weekdays and is large enough to have its own petrol station.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tesco.com/storelocator/access/details.asp?bID=3351&l=W|publisher=Tesco|accessdate=2007-10-15|title=Store Locator: Walsall Brownhills}}</ref>  Before being taken over by Tesco, the store was a branch of [[Hillards]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hillards-trust.co.uk/5302/6673.html?*session*id*key*=*session*id*val*|publisher=The Gay & Peter Hartley's Hillards Charitable Trust|title=Areas previously served by a Hillards store with radius|accessdate=2007-10-11}}</ref> and an earlier Tesco store in the town had been forced to close as it could not compete with Hillards.<ref>{{cite book |   first=Gerald|last= Reece |   title=Brownhills: A Walk Into History|   publisher=Walsall Local History Centre |   year=1996|   id=ISBN 0-9466-5242-2|pages=p49}}</ref>  

The High Street retains various independent shops, including a cobbler and a butcher, but is seen as in need of improvement. Walsall Council's regeneration programme includes extensive redevelopment of the High Street; the council's view is that retail investment should be focussed on the existing shopping area rather than encouraging new developments outside this area as, based on consultants' studies, the council believes that the town could not support large-scale retail development. Specific development opportunities within the vicinity of the High Street have been identified, with particular focus on land on Silver Street, adjacent to the canal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walsall.gov.uk/ch15_inset_brownhills.pdf|format=PDF|publisher=Walsall Council|accessdate=2007-10-15|title=Brownhills District Centre}}</ref>

==Transport==
[[Image:BrownhillsTrain.jpg|thumb|left|A train passes through Brownhills in 1909]]
Brownhills is served by the [[A5 road|A5]] and lies close to a junction of the [[M6 Toll]] motorway.  [[Travel West Midlands]] bus services connect the town with [[Walsall]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travelwm.co.uk/bus/freqresults.asp?frmSubmit=Submit&town=Birmingham&routeno=&placename=brownhills&Submit.x=26&Submit.y=23|title=Bus Route Search|publisher=Travel West Midlands|accessdate=2007-10-23}}</ref> and [[Go West Midlands|Diamond Bus]] services link to [[Aldridge]] and [[Birmingham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timetables.centro.org.uk/showtimetable.asp?file=2_a\56ABCC#56|title=Network West Midlands Bus Timetables|publisher=Centro|accessdate=2007-10-23}}</ref>  The nearest [[National Express]] coach stops are in Walsall, [[Bloxwich]] and [[Cannock]].

The [[Birmingham Canal Navigations]]' [[Wyrley and Essington Canal]] passes through Brownhills and meets the [[Daw End Branch Canal]] at [[Catshill Junction]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=36204|publisher=Victoria County History|last=Greenslade|first=M.W. (ed.)|coauthors=A P Baggs, G C Baugh, D A Johnston|chapter=Walsall Wood: Introduction|title=A History of the County of Stafford: Volume 17: Offlow hundred (part)|date=1976|pages=pp275-279}}</ref>

Brownhills formerly had two railway stations.  [[Brownhills railway station|The first,]] on the [[South Staffordshire Line]] (later part of the [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]]), opened in 1849 but was closed as part of the [[Beeching Axe]] in 1965. The line remained open for freight until 1983, but the track was lifted in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railaroundbirmingham.co.uk/Stations/brownhills.php|publisher=Rail Around Birmingham & the West Midlands|title=Brownhills Station (LNWR) 1849 <U+2013> 1965|accessdate=2007-10-15}}</ref>  [[Brownhills Watling Street railway station|The other]], on the [[Midland Railway]], was open for passengers between 1884 and 1930 and for freight until 1960, when the track was lifted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railaroundbirmingham.co.uk/Stations/brownhills_mr.php|publisher=Rail Around Birmingham & the West Midlands|title=Brownhills Station (Midland) 1884 <U+2013> 1930|accessdate=2007-10-15}}</ref>  The local authority ultimately aims to create a new station and re-open passenger rail links to Brownhills as part of its "Townscape Masterplan".<ref name="regen" />

==Education==
The town's main secondary school is Brownhills Community Technology College (formerly Brownhills Community School), a mixed-gender school with approximately {{formatnum:1000}} pupils.<ref name="Ofsted">{{cite web|url=http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/reports/pdf/?inspectionNumber=286890&providerCategoryID=8192&fileName=%5C%5Cschool%5C%5C104%5C%5Cs5_104248_20061021.pdf|format=PDF|title=Brownhills Community Technology College|accessdate=2007-10-11|publisher=Ofsted}}</ref>  In 2002 the school was designated a [[technology college]] and since 2005 has been affiliated to the [[Specialist Schools and Academies Trust]].<ref> {{cite web|url=http://www.brownhills.walsall.sch.uk/parent.htm|title=Brownhills CTC|publisher=Brownhills Community Technology College|accessdate=2007-10-11}}</ref>  In 2006, 28% of the school's pupils gained at least five [[GCSE]]s at grades A*<U+2013>C including English and maths, ranking it 12th out of Walsall's 19 secondary schools.<ref>{{cite web  | title = Schools in Walsall | publisher = BBC | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/education/06/school_tables/secondary_schools/html/335_gcse_lea.stm | date =2007-01-11 | accessdate = 2007-04-24 }}</ref> 

Although officially located slightly outside the town's boundaries in Walsall Wood,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shire-oak.walsall.sch.uk/location.htm|title=Location of Shire Oak School|publisher=Shire Oak School|accessdate=2007-10-19}}</ref> Shire Oak School takes many pupils from Brownhills. Approximately 6% of children from the town attend selective schools elsewhere in the borough of Walsall.<ref name="Ofsted2">{{cite web|url=http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/reports/pdf/?inspectionNumber=187874&providerCategoryID=8192&fileName=%5C%5Cschool%5C%5C104%5C%5Cs10_104248_20020306.pdf|format=PDF|title=Brownhills Community School|accessdate=2007-10-11|publisher=Ofsted}}</ref>

Watling Street Primary School, situated on the [[A5 road|A5]] at the western end of town, has about 200 students between the ages of 3 and 11.<ref>{{cite web  | title = Watling Street Primary School  | publisher=Department for Children, Schools and Families | url = http://www.dcsf.gov.uk/cgi-bin/performancetables/dfepx1_05.pl?No=335&Type=&Mode=&Reg=&School=3352219  | accessdate = 2007-10-24 }}</ref> In 2006, Watling Street's [[Key Stage 2]] results were the best in the Walsall area.<ref name="Primary">{{cite web  | title = Primary schools in Walsall| publisher = BBC | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/education/06/school_tables/primary_schools/html/va_335.stm| date =[[2006-12-07]] | accessdate = 2007-10-24}}</ref> There are three other primary schools in the town, St Bernadette's Catholic Primary School, Brownhills West Primary School, Millfield Primary School and one in Clayhanger, Holy Trinity Church of England Primary School.

==Religious sites==
Brownhills has a [[Church of England]] church (St James),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acny.org.uk/venue.php?V=4183|publisher=Church of England|accessdate=2007-10-15|title=St James Church, Brownhills with Ogley Hay., Brownhills}}</ref> a [[Roman Catholicism|Roman Catholic]] church (St Bernadette),<ref name="churchlinks">{{cite web|url=http://www.church-links.org.uk/Directory2/churchlinks.asp?Submit=List+Selected+Churches&mnuWard=Brownhills&mnuDenom=All&txtChurch=|publisher=Church-Links.org.uk|accessdate=2007-10-15|title=Online Directory of Churches in Walsall}}</ref> three  [[Methodism|Methodist]] churches (including one in Clayhanger),<ref name="churchlinks" /> two [[Spiritualist Church]]es,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepsychictimes.com/spchurches/westmidlands.htm|publisher=The Pyschic Times|accessdate=2007-10-15|title=West Midlands Spiritualist Churches}}</ref> and a [[Pentacostalism|Pentecostal]] church.<ref name="churchlinks" />

Brownhills has had strong links with the Methodist faith since the 19th century. The current Silver Street Methodist church was built in the 1960s when two other churches were compulsorily purchased and demolished due to their sites being identified as prime locations for additional town centre car parking under a council redevelopment scheme.<ref name="V4">{{cite book |   first=David F.|last= Vodden |   title=Britain in Old Photographs: Around Pelsall & Brownhills|   publisher=Sutton Publishing Ltd |   year=1998|   id=ISBN 0-7509-1898-5|pages=p70}}</ref>

==Culture==
===Attractions and landmarks===
[[Image:BrownhillsMiner.jpg|thumb|right|The Brownhills Miner statue]]
One of Brownhills' most prominent landmarks is a {{convert|30|ft|m|0}} sculpture of a [[coal mining|coal miner]], erected in May 2006 on a roundabout at one end of the High Street, where the A4124 Pelsall Road and High Street A452 cross. The sculpture, by John McKenna, commemorates the town's mining tradition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/west_midlands/4761283.stm|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2007-10-15|title=Giant sculpture for mining town |date=[[2006-05-11]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walsall.gov.uk/news/giant_miner_sculpture_to_rise_over_brownhills.htm|publisher=Walsall Council|accessdate=2007-10-15|date=[[2006-05-11]]|title=Giant miner sculpture to rise over Brownhills}}</ref>

[[Chasewater]] lies on the edge of Brownhills, with the area surrounding it, which is designated as a country park, officially falling within the Brownhills postal area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitlichfield.com/thedms.asp?dms=13&param1=1&venue=2200583|title= Chasewater Country Park|publisher=VisitLichfield.com|accessdate=2007-10-15}}</ref>  The reservoir supports a variety of activities including water-skiing, sailing, angling and bird watching. Running around the water is the [[Chasewater Railway]], which operates throughout the year on Sundays and also hosts a range of special events. The railway's main station is designated Brownhills West.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chasewaterrailway.co.uk/|title=There's lots to see and do at Chasewater Railway!|accessdate=2007-10-15|publisher=Chasewater Railway}}</ref>

On the opposite side of the A5, Brownhills Common, where a wide variety of birds can be observed, is a designated nature reserve,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walsall.gov.uk/index/brownhills_common_nature_reserve.htm|publisher=Walsall Council|accessdate=2007-10-15|title=Brownhills Common Nature Reserve|date=[[2007-06-19]]}}</ref> as is Shire Oak Park, approximately one mile from the town centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walsall.gov.uk/index/shire_oak_park_nature_reserve.htm|title=Shire Oak Park Local Nature Reserve|publisher=Walsall Council|accessdate=2007-10-18|date=[[2007-06-19]]}}</ref>  Holland Park, on the edge of the Common, has a skate park and multi-sports area, which were created as part of a <U+00A3>95,000 environmental regeneration project and opened in 2002. The final stage of the project will see the building of a new "youth shelter".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.walsall.gov.uk/newsdocs/NewsArticle.asp?NewsId=353|publisher=Walsall Council|accessdate=2007-10-15|title=Holland Park Skate Park Opening|date=[[2002-06-26]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walsall.gov.uk/index/brownhills_and_aldridge_district_project__holland_park.htm|publisher=Walsall Council|accessdate=2007-10-15|title=Brownhills and Aldridge District Project: Holland Park|date=[[2007-06-19]]}}</ref>

The town is home to what is reputed to be the oldest [[fingerpost]] in the United Kingdom.<ref name="Walsall">{{cite web|url=http://www2.walsall.gov.uk/CMISWebPublic/Binary.ashx?ocument=1875|publisher=Walsall Council|title=Walsall Beacon Gateways: 2nd Phase of Consultation with the LNP's|accessdate=2007-10-08}} (PDF document)</ref>

===Cultural events and venues===
[[Image:Bhillsmkt2.jpg|thumb|right|Brownhills market, with the Silver Street Methodist church visible beyond]]
One of the major concerns of the local council is that the town is "particularly lacking in leisure provision".<ref name="regen" />  At one time the town had two cinemas, but the last of these closed in the 1960s and a plan to build a new one never came to fruition.<ref name="V1">{{cite book |   first=David F.|last= Vodden |   title=Britain in Old Photographs: Around Pelsall & Brownhills|   publisher=Sutton Publishing Ltd |   year=1998|   id=ISBN 0-7509-1898-5|pages=p95}}</ref>  Although the town's theatre also closed down many years ago, the Brownhills Community School's theatre stages productions by local groups such as the Aldridge Musical Comedy Society and the Walsall Gilbert and Sullivan Society.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aldridgemcs.com/page2.htm|title=Learn all about the AMCS|publisher=Aldridge Musical Comedy Society|accessdate=2007-10-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wolverhampton.gov.uk/leisure_culture/entertainment/music/musicals_operatics/Walsall_Gilbert_and_Sullivan_Society.htm|publisher=Wolverhampton City Council|accessdate=2007-10-12|title=Walsall Gilbert and Sullivan Society}}</ref>

Brownhills holds an annual canal festival in June with stalls, entertainment and boat trips,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wowforwater.org/article.php?article_id=579|publisher=Wild Over Waterways|title=Brownhills Canal Festival|accessdate=2007-10-12}}</ref> and there is an active Community Association which organises a range of events, including a weekend-long military display event in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foreign-field.co.uk/newsarchive.html|publisher=Foreign Field Heritage and Remembrance Events|title=Foreign Field News Archive|accessdate=2007-10-12|date=[[2006-05-25]]}}</ref>  The town has a weekly market which is popular but suffers from a reputation for the sale of counterfeit goods. In 2005 Trading Standards officers seized over <U+00A3>40,000 worth of fake goods in a raid on the market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.walsall.gov.uk/newsdocs/NewsArticle.asp?NewsId=2801|publisher=Walsall Council|title=Trading Standards seize fake designer gear on market|accessdate=2007-10-12|date=[[2005-06-06]]}}</ref>

Brownhills has several [[public house]]s. Although some older ones, such as the Victorian-era Jolly Collier in Coppice Side, were demolished in the 1980s,<ref name="V2">{{cite book |   first=David F.|last= Vodden |   title=Britain in Old Photographs: Around Pelsall & Brownhills|   publisher=Sutton Publishing Ltd |   year=1998|   id=ISBN 0-7509-1898-5|pages=p21}}</ref> several dating from the 19th century still stand comparatively unchanged, including the Shoulder of Mutton, which still bears windows etched with the emblem of the brewery which owned it in the 1850s.<ref name="V3">{{cite book |   first=David F.|last= Vodden |   title=Britain in Old Photographs: Around Pelsall & Brownhills|   publisher=Sutton Publishing Ltd |   year=1998|   id=ISBN 0-7509-1898-5|pages=p27}}</ref>

===Sport===
Brownhills does not currently have a Saturday men's [[football (soccer)]] team, the nearest being [[Pelsall Villa F.C.]] of the [[West Midlands Regional League]] and [[Heath Hayes F.C.]] and [[Walsall Wood F.C.]] of the [[Midland Football Combination]]. In the 1990s Brownhills Town F.C. competed in the Combination but folded during the [[2003-04 in English football|2003&ndash;04]] season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fchd.info/BROWNHIT.HTM|title=Brownhills Town|publisher=The Football Club History Database|accessdate=2007-10-12}}</ref>  During the 1950s Ogley Hay F.C. were a strong local team, reaching the final of the [[Walsall Senior Cup]] on three occasions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wmrl.non-league.org/Walsall_Senior_Cup.htm|publisher=West Midlands (Regional) League|title=Walsall Senior Cup|accessdate=2007-10-12}}</ref>  Currently, the main football club in the town is Brownhills Community Colts, a youth club which has existed since the 1970s and fields teams in various age groups, as well as teams for children with disabilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bccfc.com/about.htm|title=About Our Club|publisher=Brownhills Community Colts Football Club|accessdate=2007-10-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blackcountry/content/articles/2006/04/26/brownhills_disabled_kids_footy_feature.shtml|publisher=BBC|title=Football for disabled youngsters in Brownhills|author=Keith Raison|accessdate=2007-10-12|date=[[2006-04-26]]}}</ref>

The Brownhills Canoe and Outdoor Centre opened in 2006, funded by [[British Waterways]] with the assistance of partners such as [[Sport England]], the [[European Regional Development Fund]] and [[Metropolitan Borough of Walsall|Walsall Council]], and offers [[canoeing]] and [[kayaking]] lessons on the canal, close to the centre of town.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishwaterways.co.uk/newsroom/stories/Paddling_their_way_to_success.html|publisher=British Waterways|title=Paddling their way to success|accessdate=2007-10-12|date=[[2006-08-25]]}}</ref>  Nearby Chasewater is a prominent watersports site, with the Watersports Centre offering a variety of [[water skiing]] facilities, including the largest children's coaching scheme in the UK,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chasewaterski.co.uk/about.php|publisher=Chase Watersports Centre|title=About|accessdate=2007-10-24}}</ref> and the sailing club providing year-round [[windsurfing]] and [[dinghy sailing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chasesc.org.uk/sailing.htm|publisher=Chase Sailing Club|title=Sailing|accessdate=2007-10-24}}</ref>

The local community association organises a range of sporting activities for members of the public, including activities as diverse as [[yoga]], [[badminton]] and [[kickboxing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.walsall.gov.uk/leisure/sportsrecreation/display2.asp?search=Area&id=11|publisher=Walsall Council|title=East|accessdate=2007-10-12}}</ref>

===Media===
Brownhills has no dedicated local newspaper of its own, but is covered by newspapers published in [[Wolverhampton]] and [[Walsall]]. The most popular paid-for local newspaper is the ''[[Express & Star]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsdatabase.co.uk/newspaperdetail.cfm?paperid=389|title=West Midlands Express & Star |publisher=The Newspaper Society|accessdate=2007-10-23}}</ref> Free newspapers with significant circulation in the town include the ''Walsall Chronicle'', ''Walsall Advertiser'', and ''Walsall Observer''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsdatabase.co.uk/newspaperdetail.cfm?paperid=1093|title=Walsall Observer|publisher=The Newspaper Society|accessdate=2007-10-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsdatabase.co.uk/newspaperdetail.cfm?paperid=1089|title=Walsall Advertiser|publisher=The Newspaper Society|accessdate=2007-10-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsdatabase.co.uk/newspaperdetail.cfm?paperid=1091|title=Walsall Chronicle|publisher=The Newspaper Society|accessdate=2007-10-23}}</ref>  Similarly, the town has no dedicated local radio station but receives the stations broadcast from the [[Sutton Coldfield transmitting station]], including [[BRMB]] and [[Kerrang! 105.2]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ofcom.org.uk/static/radiolicensing/mcamaps/al288.pdf|format=PDF|title=Analogue Broadcast Radio Measured Coverage Area (MCA) Maps|publisher=Ofcom|accessdate=2007-10-24|date=[[2004-09-28]]}}</ref>

==Notable people==
Three members of the Dorsett family from Brownhills played professional [[football (soccer)]].  [[George Dorsett]] (1881&ndash;1942) and his brother [[Joe Dorsett|Joe]] (1888&ndash;1951) both played for [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in the early years of the 20th century.<ref name="Roy">{{cite book |   first=Michael|last=Joyce |   title=Football League Players' Records 1888 <U+2013> 1939|   publisher=Tony Brown |   year=2004|   id=ISBN 1-8994-6867-6|pages=p77}}</ref>  Their nephew [[Dicky Dorsett]] (born [[3 December]] [[1919]], died 1999) played over 250 times for [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] between 1946 and 1952 and also played for [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] in the 1939 [[FA Cup final]].<ref>{{cite book |   first=Barry J.|last= Hugman |   title=Canon League Football Players' Records 1946-1984|   publisher=Newnes Books |   year=1984|   id=ISBN 0-6003-7318-5|pages=p125}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewolvessite.co.uk/ddorsett.htm|title=Dicky Dorsett|publisher=The Wolves Site|accessdate=2007-10-12}}</ref>  More recently, [[supermodel]]  [[Erin O'Connor]] (born [[9 February]] [[1978]]) grew up in Brownhills.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://driving.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/driving/article1315713.ece|publisher=The Times|title=On the move: Erin O'Connor|accessdate=2007-10-11|date=[[2007-02-04]]|author=Emma Smith}}</ref>

